John Edward: Language skills are a key skill for a global citizen
The educational achievements of private schools in Scotland have traditionally been good, and this success has continued in 2018 as a result of good test results. This success has been enhanced by individual and community success in sports, arts, music and other community projects.
These schools of over 30,000 pupils across Scotland, represented by SCIS, the Scottish Council of Private Schools, strive to provide a high level of service to their pupils and their parents.
Private schools aim to prepare their students for careers of their choice, for postgraduate and higher education, and for world citizenship.
As an actor in the education sector that can design and implement tailored study content, we have noticed the position of languages as a popular and desirable subject in educational institutions.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to someone in a language they understand, the message goes to their heads.
If you speak to a person in his or her own language, the message goes to his or her heart.”
This is a strong reminder that we cannot rely only on English if we want to build relationships of trust with people from other countries.
From this year’s latest test results, we can see that languages are at the top of the lists in terms of the pass rate among private schools.
68% of pupils who studied foreign languages achieved the highest grade of A.
The data was collected from 74 SCIS schools and found that 72% of pupils with the highest grade A studied Mandarin, 72% studied German, 69% studied French and 63% studied Spanish.
This shows that Scottish private schools support foreign language learning as an essential skill that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are currently optional subjects, but they are valued in the same way as science subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics), both in the curriculum of private schools and elsewhere.
A survey commissioned by the UK Employment Office in 2014 found that 17 per cent of situations where an employer had difficulty finding a suitable employee were explained by lack of language skills.
The development of language skills is therefore even more necessary in order to promote young people's future career development.
The more possible jobs require language skills, the more essential these skills become in the global world.
If a person has studied a second language, he or she will have an advantage in the future of this lifelong skill, regardless of the career he or she has chosen.
The ability to communicate directly with a foreigner automatically puts a person with language skills ahead of the competition.
According to a 2013 survey commissioned by YouGov, 75% of over 4,000 British adults are unable to speak a foreign language, and French was the only language to be understood with a two-digit figure of 15%.
This is why it is important to invest in language teaching for today’s children.
In particular, knowledge of the languages of developing countries gives children a better chance to find a meaningful career.
Within Scotland, schools differ in what languages they teach.
Several schools focus on traditional languages, while some specifically teach languages that are supposed to be important to British people in 2020, such as Mandarin Chinese and Japanese.
Regardless of your child’s interests, there are always several language options in private schools taught by specialized teachers.
Scottish private schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills needed to succeed, whatever the future may bring.
At this time, it cannot be denied that in the international business environment, languages will continue to be very important for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should indeed be seen as 'international communication skills'.
Private schools will continue to offer this freedom of choice, diversity and high standards to young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the head of SCIS, the Scottish Council of Private Schools.
