Harvard Students Take A Course Instructing Sufficient Rest
This year, all undergraduate students at Harvard University will take part in a course designed to increase student rest. The course is a setback to the university’s flourishing macho culture, where students weigh long nights with the power of caffeine.
According to the researcher, students at the best university in the world are often quite ignorant about the basics of their own well-being.
Designed by Charles Czeisler, a professor at Harvard Medical School who works on sleep research at Brigham and Women’s Hospital, the course is believed to be the first of its kind in the United States.
Czeisler had an idea for the course after giving lectures on the impact of sleep deficiency on learning.
"After the lecture, a young woman came to me and said, 'Why do I only hear about it now, in my final year of school?'
No one had ever told him about the need for sleep, which I found surprising,” he said in an interview with the Telegraph.
For the first time this year, the course will guide students on how the right unity habits support academic and athletic performance and improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of medicine at Harvard University and vice president of health services at the university, said the university ended up arranging a course after hearing how students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during their study week.
The one-hour course includes a set of interactive tasks.
In one section, students are presented with a picture of a dormitory room where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sports equipment and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the effect of sleep deprivation on sports performance and the importance of regular evening activities.
The second section tells participants how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to reflect on their daily routines.
“We know that this does not have an immediate impact on student behavior.
We believe, however, that they have the right to know about these issues just as they have the right to know about the health effects of smoking,” Professor Czeisler adds.
According to Professor Czeisler, all-night study marathons are still a matter of pride, and modern technology and the ever-increasing pressures on students made sleep deprivation a growing problem.
"Getting enough and high-quality sleep should be a student's 'secret weapon' against stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, and even weight gain, because sleep deprivation causes a state in the brain that resembles starvation, which is why people are constantly hungry," the professor points out.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student of chemical and physical psychology from California, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his courses in his first year at Harvard last year.
He says that the course opened his eyes and gave him the impetus to organize a comprehensive course for all the students on campus.
He hopes that all postgraduate students could complete a similar study package before moving to a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler advises students to set an alarm clock to remind them of bedtime in addition to waking up in the morning, and also advises them to keep in mind the adverse effects of “blue light” on the circadian rhythm caused by electronic display devices and LED lighting, which can make it difficult to fall asleep.
