New Cancer Vaccine Can Teach the Immune System to ‘See’ Malignant Cells
New cancer vaccine can teach the immune system to ‘see’ malignant cells and destroy them
Vaccine teaches the immune system to recognize malignant cells as part of treatment
The method involves isolating resistant cells from the patient and modifying them in the laboratory
After treatment, the cells injected back into the body are able to ‘see’ proteins typical of several cancers
The dog vaccine has produced promising results in patients with various types of cancer.
For example, a patient with ovarian cancer lost cancer cells within 18 months after being treated with a vaccine that teaches the immune system to recognise malignant cells.
In this method, resistant cells are isolated from the patient and modified in the laboratory so that they can ‘see’ the HER2 proteins typical of several cancers. The modified cells are then injected back into the body.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, U.S.A., describes the method: “Our results show that this is a very promising vaccine.”
HER2 "controls the growth of several types of cancer," Professor Berzofsky explains. "This includes breast cancer, as well as ovarian, lung and colon cancers."
A similar approach —to take resistant cells from a patient and teach them to attack cancer cells— has also yielded results in treating a type of leukaemia.
