HIV/AIDS: The number of new infections in China has increased by 14%
China has reported a 14% increase in the number of its citizens living with HIV and AIDS.
According to health authorities, the virus affects the lives of more than 820,000 people in the country.
Approximately 40,000 new cases have been reported in the second quarter of 2018 alone.
The overwhelming majority of new cases have been transmitted through sex, which represents a change from previous statistics.
Traditionally, HIV has spread rapidly in parts of China through contaminated blood transfusions.
However, according to Chinese health authorities at a conference in Yunnan province, the number of HIV infections that have occurred in this way has been reduced to almost zero.
A year later, however, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China has increased by 100,000.
Sexually transmitted HIV is an acute issue in the LGBT community in China.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people has been reported to be widespread.
Studies have estimated that, due to the conservative values of the country, 70-90% of men who have sex with men will eventually marry women.
Many infections are caused by inadequate protection in such relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has pledged to guarantee universal access to HIV medicines as part of efforts to address the problem.
