What is the Global Citizen Festival and what has it done to reduce poverty?
The Global Citizen Festival, which takes place in New York on Saturday, is a music event with an impressive line-up of performers as its mission: to eradicate poverty in the world.
This is the seventh Global Citizen Festival to attract tens of thousands of people to the New York City Central Park grasslands to listen to performers like Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but also to make known the true goal of the event: to eradicate extreme poverty by 2030.
Launched in 2012, Global Citizen Festival is a continuation of the Global Power Project, an international advisory group that aims to eradicate poverty by increasing the number of people actively working to eradicate poverty.
In order to receive a free ticket to an event (unless you are willing to pay for a VIP ticket), the audience must perform various tasks or “deeds”, such as volunteering, sending an email to a political decision maker or making a call, or perform any other act that spreads awareness of the goals of the project.
But how has Global Citizen succeeded, now that it’s only 12 years away?
Is the idea of rewarding people with a free concert ticket a real way to persuade people to take action, or is it just one of those ‘clictivism’ among others – the idea that you can change the world by signing an online address or sending a tweet?
Global Citizen has recorded more than 19 million “deeds” for various purposes since 2011.
These actions have encouraged policymakers to announce commitments and principles equivalent to more than <0x24>37 billion, which have been spent in ways that will affect the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
In early 2018, the group listed 390 commitments and statements on the basis of which more than <0x24>10 billion has already been spent or raised.
The group estimates that the funds raised have already affected the lives of nearly 649 million people worldwide.
Key commitments include The Power of Nutrition, a UK-based group of investors and executives committed to “helping children develop to their full potential”. The group committed to deliver <0x24>35 million to Rwanda to end malnutrition in the country, after activists sent them 4,700 tweets as a result of the Global Citizen campaign.
"Thanks to the British government, donors, governments of different countries, and global citizens just like you, we can bring social injustice and malnutrition to the press," Power of Nutrition Ambassador Tracey Ullman told an audience at a concert in London in 2018.
According to the group, the British government was also called upon to take action to improve mothers’ and children’s nutrition through more than 5,000 actions. The government has announced funding for the Power on Nutrition project, which focuses on combating malnutrition, reaching 5 million mothers and children.
One of the frequently asked questions on the movement’s website is, “Why do you think we can end extreme poverty?”
Global Citizen’s answer: “The road will be long and difficult and there are many stumbling blocks ahead of us.
But we will succeed, like the great civil rights struggles and the anti-apartheid movements before us, because together we are stronger.”
Deborra-Lee Furness and Hugh Jackman will host the show at a New York concert this year, and its star squadron includes artists such as Janet Jackson, the Weeknd, Shawn Mendes, Cardi B and Janelle Monáe.
