World Wide Web inventor plans to launch new internet as a counter-attack to Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, has launched a startup to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of the technology legend, Inrupt, is a company based on Berners-Lee’s open source Solid platform.
Solid allows users to decide where their data is stored and who has access to which data.
In an interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee jokes about Inrupt's goal of "dominating the world."
"It has to be done now," he said, referring to his startup.
“This is a historic moment.”
The application uses Solid’s technology to allow people to create their own “personal data warehouse” or POD.
It can include contact lists, note lists, calendar, music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It’s like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify all available in one browser at the same time.
What is unique about a personal repository is that it is completely up to the user who has access to what type of information.
The company calls it “personal empowerment through information.”
According to John Bruce, CEO of the company, Inrupt’s idea is to provide the resources, processes, and skills needed to bring Solid to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, the security platform purchased by IBM, some paid developers working with the project, and a community of volunteer coders.
Technology developers around the world can create their own distributed applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website. All of this will be available from this week onwards.
Berners-Lee says he and his team will not discuss with Facebook and Google whether people should be offered a complete change in which all of their business models are turned on their heads overnight.
“We’re not asking for their consent.”
In an article in Medium on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt's "mission is to provide commercial energy and ecosystem for the coherence and quality of the new Solid-built grid."
In 1994, Berners-Lee revolutionized the Internet by establishing the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate on net neutrality.
Berners-Lee remains the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute even after the launch of Inrupt.
"I am extremely optimistic about the next era of the network," Berners-Lee added.
